President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum, and the boycott campaign raised doubts about whether the turnout would reach the minimum 50 percent needed for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the referendum ballot was: “Are you in favour of membership of the European Union and NATO through the recognition of the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Republic of Greece?”
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a prize worth admitting Macedonia, a country that emerged after the demise of Yugoslavia, to communities such as the EU and NATO.
“I came here today to vote for a future for the country, for young people in Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the auspices of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us,” said Olivera Georgiyevska, 79, from Skopje.
Although the vote is not legally binding, enough parliamentarians have declared that they will respect the will of the voters and make decisions based on the result.
A change of name would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that there were no irregularities during the referendum until 13:00.
However, turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters voted.
“I came to vote for my children, our place lies in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter in the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian MP Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their ballots in the Macedonian referendum on changing the country's name to join NATO and the European Union in the Macedonian city of Strumica on September 30, 2018.
Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, erected a small podium in front of the parliament in Skopje and dragged the chairs in front of tents erected by opponents who wanted to boycott the referendum.
“We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to enter them with our heads held high, not through the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We may be poor, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia and become part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
“I am convinced that the vast majority will be in favour, because more than 80 percent of our citizens support the EU and NATO,” Zaev said after casting his ballot.
He added that the resulting “yes” would be “a confirmation of our future.”
