“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, cut off from the sea, hopes to restore access to the Pacific Ocean
Sailors besiege the naval headquarters at La Paz dressed in sails.
There are blue flags in public buildings.
Marine bases from Lake Titikaka to the Amazon are emblazoned with the motto: “The sea is our right.
Getting it back is our duty.”
Across Bolivia, cut off from the sea, the memory of the coast lost to Chile in the bloody conflict of the 19th century is still alive - as is the desire to sail the waters of the Pacific Ocean once again.
After five years of hearings, Bolivia is awaiting a ruling by the International Court of Justice on October 1.
“Bolivia is on the rise, it has a spirit of unity and equanimity, and of course it believes in a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the decision of the international court on big screens across the country in the hope that the tribunal in The Hague will decide in favor of Bolivia, so that after decades of intermittent negotiations, Chile is obliged to negotiate to provide sovereign access to the sea of Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, who will take part in a controversial re-election battle next year, also has something to say about Monday’s decision.
“Our return to the Pacific Ocean is within reach,” he said at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will rule in Bolivia’s favor - and if it did, not much would change.
The UN body based in the Netherlands does not have the authority to allocate Chilean territory and said it would not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the ruling comes only six months after hearing the final arguments suggests that the case “wasn’t complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And while there can be no doubt about Bolivian arguments, it is possible that it has taken a step backwards in recent years.
“The issue of access to the sea has been appropriated by the current Bolivian government,” said Zarate.
Morales’s aggressive rhetoric undermined all remaining friendliness with Chile, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to negotiate one day, but after that it will be very difficult to maintain dialogue.
The two countries have not had each other's embassies since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, dismissed the idea that the court's decision would be unusually quick.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance “to end 139 years of disagreement and achieve mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also dismissed the claim that Morales, still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, would use the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean,” he said.
“Decision is an opportunity to realize that we must overcome the past.”
