John Edward: Without language skills, a global citizen cannot do
Scottish independent schools maintain excellent academic performance and this trend continues in 2018 with another year of extraordinary exam results, further strengthening individual and collective achievements in sports, arts, music and other social activities.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare students for further and higher education, careers as they see fit, and a place in the world as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement tailor-made curricula, we still perceive modern languages as a popular and sought-after selective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “When you speak to a man in a language he understands, you are speaking to his head.
When you speak to him in his own language, you are speaking to his heart.”
It is a strong reminder that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
From this year’s exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the table with the highest grade average among independent schools.
Overall, 68 percent of pupils who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved the highest A grade in Mandarin Chinese, 72 percent in German, 69 percent in French, and 63 percent in Spanish.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland promote foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages are considered to be as important as STEM subjects (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) as selection subjects in independent and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that 17 percent of the reasons employers cited as problems in filling jobs were lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more promising job opportunities arise that are required by languages, these skills become essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses, if he learned a second language, with such a lifelong ability he will have a real advantage for the future.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give a multilingual person an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak any foreign language sufficiently to be able to converse fluently, with French being the only language in which many people fell into double-digit percentages (15 percent).
Therefore, it is important for today's children to invest in language learning.
Knowledge of multiple languages, especially the languages of advanced economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will vary according to the languages it teaches.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK in terms of the future in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, independent schools will always be able to choose from a variety of languages and will be taught by experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
At present, it cannot be denied that, in the global business environment, languages remain crucial for the country's future, and this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be called “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools.
