North Korea will not unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions had deepened mistrust of the United States and that the country would in no way unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea has taken "substantial steps" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and pledging not to expand nuclear weapons and technology.
“We don’t see any response from the United States,” he added.
“Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and in such circumstances, it is out of the question that we will be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s opposition to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual steps, his position was crucial in not immediately rejecting unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between the current US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump promised North Korea a guarantee of security.
North Korea sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States declared that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to release strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists first on nuclear disarmament and increases the level of tension through sanctions to achieve its purpose in a coercive way and even by objecting to the ‘declaration of an end to war,’” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions will bring us to our knees is an illusion of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are deepening our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim Jong Un and Trump, which the U.S. president told the United Nations earlier this week.
However, he stressed three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other side of the nuclear disarmament issue was South Korea instead of the US, the disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a dead end.”
Still, Ri’s tone was dramatically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting U.S. territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after “President Evil” Trump called Kim a “rocket on a suicide mission.”
This year, Trump, who threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea last year, sang at the UN praising Kim for his courage in taking disarmament action, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and sanctions must remain until North Korea is cleared of nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a timetable for the move, adding: “It doesn’t matter if it takes two, three years or five months.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the application of the Security Council’s sanctions must continue rigorously and without exception until we have achieved complete, final and verified nuclear disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an effort to throttle funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and subsequently said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for the second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit was not a good one.
In July, he left Pyongyang, saying progress had been made, but hours later, North Korea condemned him for making “gangster demands.”
At a meeting with Moon earlier this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle both the missile test site and the nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim told him that the “appropriate measures” he expected were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Take a Course on How to Get Enough Rest
The goal of this year’s new course at Harvard University is for all students to get more sleep in an effort to curb the growing trend of studying throughout the night with the help of caffeine.
Researchers have found that students at the world’s leading university are often baffled when it comes to the very basics of taking care of their health.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Clinic, has developed a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to set up the course after a lecture he gave on sleep deprivation and its impact on learning.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about this now, in my senior year?’
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, which took place for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help both academic and sports performance while improving general health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health service, said the university had decided to open the course when it discovered that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the workweek.
The course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, the screen shows a picture of a boarding room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books, and learn about the effects of caffeine, light, and how lack of sleep affects athletic performance and how important a regular sleep schedule is.
In the next section, participants will learn how long-term sleep deficits can increase their risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The map of the university campus with interactive icons also encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that it won’t change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe that they have a right to know about it - just as everyone has a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
There is still a culture in which students are proud of being able to learn all night long, she says, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students means sleep deprivation has become a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate, good-quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said, even against weight gain, as sleep deficits put the brain into starvation mode, leaving them constantly feeling hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his seminars last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to pursue the course at the university level.
It hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar course of study before embarking on a demanding course of study.
Prof. Czeisler advises students to set an alarm both for when to go to bed and for when to wake up, and to become aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting that can disrupt your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble falling asleep.
