The National Trust reveals the secret life of bats
New research is underway on a manor in the Scottish Highlands to uncover how bats are using the land to hunt for food.
We hope that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
A study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow bats whistling and squeaking bats, as well as light-footed bats and water bats in the Inverewe gardens in the Wester Ross area.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to keep track of bat activities throughout the season.
Employees of this organization and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Professional sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat calls and the activities of individual species.
They then create a map of their natural environment and a report to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a large scale.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the natural environment are most important to bats and how they are used by individual species.
This information will help determine the benefits of environmental management work, such as meadow formation and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
Populations of bats in Scotland and the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development works that affect grassland and the loss of the environment.
Wind turbines and lighting, as well as airplanes and some chemical modifications to building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks, can also be a danger.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are like eyes when it comes to prey hunting.
They use sophisticated echolocation techniques to pinpoint insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained professionals who regularly conduct surveys, inspections of assembly points, and sometimes rescues.
The organization has even established the first and only dedicated bat protected area on the Threeve estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten species of bats in Scotland.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says the estate is an ideal territory for them.
“Here in Threave, we have a wonderful space for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of protected trees and all the good habitats.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to survive.”
It stresses the importance of controlling bats before carrying out maintenance on the property, as it is possible that the unconscious destruction of one parent site could kill up to 400 females and chicks, which would probably destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is against the law to kill, abuse, disturb or destroy their gathering places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to get involved in helping.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know how many of our species feed on them.”
